    // If G is present in the array, we can replace every element with G.
    // However, G might not be present initially.

    // Let S be the set of unique values in nums.
    // The smallest value an element nums[a] can become is the minimum element 'd' in S such that nums[a] % d == 0,
    // or more generally, the smallest element reachable by division chains.

    // The crucial observation (from similar problems): the final set of values must consist of elements that
    // are mutually irreducible under this operation, and these irreducible values are determined by the divisors present.

    // If we can reduce all numbers to their GCD, that's the minimum.
    // The GCD of the whole array, G, is the smallest number that divides every element.
    // If we can make every element equal to G, the sum is N * G.

    // Can we always reduce every element nums[i] to G?
    // If we have nums[i], we want to replace it with G. This requires a chain of divisors leading to G.
    // If G is a divisor of all nums[i], and G is present in the array, yes.

    // If G is not present, but we have a sequence of divisors d1, d2, ..., dk=G available,
    // we can replace nums[i] with d1, then d2, ..., dk.

    // Since we can pick ANY two indices a and b, if there exists ANY divisor 'd' of nums[a] present in the array (nums[b]=d),
    // we can replace nums[a] with 'd'.

    // This means every number nums[i] can be reduced to the smallest element 'd' in the *initial* set S such that d divides nums[i].
    // Wait, this is not entirely true because the set S changes.

    // Example 1: [3, 6, 2]. S={2, 3, 6}.
    // 6 % 2 == 0 -> [3, 2, 2]. New S'={2, 3}.
    // 3 % 2 != 0. 3 % 3 == 0 (no change). 2 % 2 == 0 (no change). Sum = 7.
    // Smallest divisor of 6 in S is 2. 6 -> 2.
    // Smallest divisor of 3 in S is 3. 3 -> 3.
    // Smallest divisor of 2 in S is 2. 2 -> 2.
    // If we only look at initial divisors: [3, 2, 2]. Sum 7. Matches.

    // Example 2: [4, 2, 8, 3]. S={2, 3, 4, 8}.
    // 4 % 2 == 0 -> [2, 2, 8, 3].
    // 8 % 2 == 0 -> [2, 2, 2, 3]. New S'={2, 3}.
    // 3 % 2 != 0. 3 % 3 == 0.
    // Final sum = 2 + 2 + 2 + 3 = 9. Matches.

    // It seems that every element nums[i] will be replaced by the smallest number d that is *reachable* from the initial set and divides nums[i].
    // Since any divisor present in the array can be used, this suggests we should find the GCD of all numbers that can participate in the reduction.

    // The set of values that can possibly end up in the array are the divisors of the initial numbers that are themselves reachable divisors.
    // Since the operation only replaces a number with a *divisor* already present, the set of achievable values is restricted.

