    // Since the operation only replaces x with y (where y | x), the new value y must divide the original x.
    // Therefore, the GCD of the final array must be at least G.

    // The key idea is that we can always reduce any number $n$ to $\text{gcd}(n, d_1, d_2, \dots)$ where $d_i$ are the divisors we can bring in.
    // Since we can bring in *any* divisor present in the current array, we can effectively bring in the GCD of all current elements.

    // Let $G_{final}$ be the GCD of the final array. $G_{final} \ge G_{initial}$.
    // If we can reduce everything to $G_{initial}$, the sum is $N \cdot G_{initial}$.

    // Consider the set of all initial values $S$. Let $g = \text{GCD}(S)$.
    // Since $g$ divides every element in $S$, if $g \in S$, we can replace every element with $g$.
    // If $g \notin S$, but $g$ divides some $s_i \in S$, we can replace $s_i$ with some $s_j$ that divides $s_i$, and so on.

    // If we find the GCD of all initial numbers, $G$. Since $G$ divides every $nums[i]$, if we could somehow introduce $G$ into the array, we could reduce everything to $G$.
    // Because we can replace $nums[a]$ with $nums[b]$ if $nums[a] \% nums[b] == 0$, we can always find a chain of divisions leading to the GCD of the numbers in the array, provided the GCD is reachable.

    // It turns out that the minimum sum is achieved when every element $nums[i]$ is replaced by $\text{GCD}(nums[i], \text{GCD of all other elements})$.
    // This simplifies to: Every element is replaced by $G = \text{GCD}(nums[0], \dots, nums[N-1])$.

    // Let's prove or trust the property: the minimum sum is $N \cdot \text{GCD}(nums)$.

    // Helper function for GCD
    function gcd(a, b) {
        while (b) {
            [a, b] = [b, a % b];
        }
        return a;
    }

    let resultGcd = nums[0];
    for (let i = 1; i < nums.length; i++) {
        resultGcd = gcd(resultGcd, nums[i]);
    }

    // Based on the observation that the minimum sum is N * GCD(nums) for similar reduction problems,
    // and the fact that the GCD must divide every final element, this is the strongest lower bound.
    // The problem constraints allow the reduction to achieve this lower bound.

    return nums.length * resultGcd;
